[Student "S"]
{North is to play 6\S. East leads the \HQ.

This \D holding is the third example shown in the introduction.

This is another follow-up to Deal 1. But this time you are missing both the \DQ and \DJ. In this case an Elimination play doesn't give you a guarantee, it just improves your odds.

Win the first trick and play \SA, \SK. Trumps split 2-1.

Play three rounds of \Cs to eliminate the suit from you and dummy.

Now execute the throw-in by leading a \H from either hand.

The defender who gets thrown in cannot play a \H or a \C without handing you the contract by way of a ruff-and-sluff. So he must lead a \D. Suppose it is East who leads the \D. You play low in dummy and West must play either the \DQ or \DJ to keep you from getting a cheap trick with your \D9. So you take West's honor with your \DA and then finesse East for the other honor. As long as the \DQ and \DJ are in different hands the elimination play will succeed.

Against good defenders there is no way you can make all three \D tricks if you make the first play in the suit. This assumes that if one defender held both the \DQ and \DJ he would "split" the honors if you tried to lead through them. 

By forcing them to start the \Ds you make three tricks when the two outstanding honors are divided. }
[Play "W"]HQ

